      <body>
         <div type="entry">
                <head>Dawid bar Pawlos</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Dawid-bar-Pawlos</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/167</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">158</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="116-117"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/144</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Abbot and author or poetry and prose; wrote on theology, grammar, science.<note>brief</note>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(8th/9th <abbr>cent.</abbr>) [<abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Author. Born in Beth Shahaq, in the region of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Nineveh">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/144">Nineveh</placeName>
                        </ref>, he was
                        abbot of the monastery of Mor Sargis, on the Dry Mountain in Sinjar. A
                        marginal note to Dolabani no. 2, states that in 785 (cf. Mingana Syr. 29 for
                        the year) he temporarily moved with others to a monastery on the Euphrates
                        (evidently <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Qenneshre-Monastery-of">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/230">Qenneshre</placeName>
                        </ref>) and later brought back 170 <hi rend="italic">maʿnyoto</hi> of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Severus-of-Antioch">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/51">Severus</persName>
                        </ref>, adapting
                        them for liturgical use in the east. The texts published by Dolabani are
                        mainly letters, prose, and verse, in a learned style, to named
                        correspondents; of particular interest are no.  6, on the authorship of
                        Wisdom (Maccabean date), and no. 14 (<abbr>LT</abbr> in Rahmani, 44–6), on points in
                        biblical <abbr>mss.</abbr>, with reference to several scholars. At the end are two longer
                        poems, on the 7
                        <hi rend="italic"> klimata</hi> (also <abbr>ed.</abbr> by Cardahi and
                        Gottheil from different <choice>
                            <sic>mss</sic>
                            <corr>mss.</corr>
                        </choice>), and one on the trees and plants and their
                        symbolism (the first part is given in <hi rend="italic">Qolo Suryoyo</hi> 56
                        [1987], 153–49). He is also author of some short grammatical works (partial
                        <abbr>ed.</abbr> Gottheil), a poem on the alphabet (<abbr>ed.</abbr> Gottheil), a commentary on
                        Genesis 10 (in <abbr>ms.</abbr> British Libr. Add. 14,620; incomplete) and a dialogue
                        with a Melkite on the Trisagion (excerpt in <hi rend="italic">BibOr</hi>,
                        vol. 1, 518–9). The attribution to him of the 22 short poems (forming an
                        alphabetic acrostic) published by Qarabashi cannot be correct: each poem
                        contains only a single example of its opening letter, a type of composition,
                        as Barsoum points out, which does not otherwise appear till the 13th
                        <abbr>cent.</abbr>
                    </p>
                </div>
